==English==

===Etymology===
Latin ''urgere''; akin to English ''wreak''.

===Noun===
'''urge''' (plural: [[urges]])
#An [[impulse]]; an [[itch]] to do something.

===Verb===
'''urge'''

[[transitive]]: '''urge''', '''[[urged]]''', '''[[urging]]'''
#To press; to [[push]]; to drive; to [[impel]]; to force [[onward]].
#To press the mind or will of; to [[ply]] with motives, [[argument]]s, [[persuade|persuasion]], or [[importunity]].
#To [[provoke]]; to [[exasperate]].
#To present in an urgent manner; to [[insist]] upon.
#''(obsolete)'': To treat with forcible means; to take severe or violent measures with; as, to urge an ore with intense heat. Syn. -- To animate; incite; impel; instigate; stimulate; encourage. 
[[intransitive]]: '''urge'''
#To press onward or forward.
#To be pressing in argument; to insist; to persist.

